description:
Unlike most previous titles in The Europa Series, The Urals module is not a game playable in itself. Instead, it is a module containing Europa material on the Ural Mountains region during World War II. Prior ownership of both Scorched Earth and Fire in the East is necessary to use The Urals module. The components contained in The Urals module are presented at standard Europa scales. Also included is information on combining this module for play with Fire in the East/Scorched Earth.

The Urals module contains the following components;
1. Four maps (Europa maps 28, 29, 30 and 31) covering the Ural Mountains at a scale of 16 miles per hex;
2. One chart set, consisting of charts necessary to link The Urals module to Fire in the East/Scorched Earth;
3. A revised Soviet Order of Battle providing minor revisions as well as detailed information on those units raised in the Urals, Siberian, Central Asian, Transbaikal and Far Eastern Military Districts that appear in Fire in the East/Scorched Earth;
4. A rules booklet for combining The Urals with Fire in the East/Scorched Earth.
5. 50% reductions of maps 28, 29, 30 and 31 for use as the player desires;
6. An errata sheet covering Fire in the East/Scorched Earth/The Urals;
7. The 1943 campaign and grand campaign Axis and Soviet orders of battle and deployment maps.

Sub-title:"The East Prussian Campaign 1914". The Imperial German Army's successful opening battles of encirclement and destruction of the Imperial Russian 2nd Army at the opening of World War 1.

Contents include a Ziploc baggie, a 17"x22" paper map sheet, 2-page rules folder, die-cut thin paper counters, and a paper sheet with the Combat Results Table/Terrain Effects Chart/Turn Record Track/Reinforcements Schedule. Players must provide their own die.

The map sheet is mostly tan with blue national territory lettering, forest and water features and brown for all other terrain including single & double rail lines, towns/cities, borders, fieldworks, detached and ring forts, and place names. Counters are white with green print (Russians) and green with white print (Germans) and represent Brigade/Divisional level Combat units.

The rules folder has a listing of abbreviations. On the back page are the victory conditions, addenda, design notes and scenarios including some optional set-ups. Additional options include:

A.Stronger German 8th Army; 
B.Stronger Russian 2nd Army; 
C.Better Russian Mobilization; 
D.Better Russian Cavalry.

The game runs from August 17th, 1914 through September 15th, 1914 and each turn represents 1 day while each hex is considered to be 3 miles across from side to side. The playing area covers East Prussian Germany down to north Russian Poland.

The Russian moves first and the Sequence of Play is as follows:

1.Supply Judgement phase; 
2.Movement phase; 
3.Combat phase,

followed by the German Player's turn. There are Special Rules for Cavalry, Landsturm, Fortifications & Fieldworks, and Hidden (inverted) units.

This is a very concise and easy to learn game as is most of the company's products while being one of the first produced by them to have die-cut counters.

This is the first expansion module for the Avalon Hill miniatures based game of Napoleon's Battles. It is a 54-pages Booklet with 'Errata' & clarifications for the 1st game, additional Terrain features, with 9 more Scenarios, the Divisional Armies Structured Army Charts, Additional Optional Rules, even MORE labels for these Scenarios, a set of BLANK 'generic' Officers labels and a BLANK information chart for further uses.

The Scenarios covered in this are: 
S-9.The Battle of Valmy, Sept.20,1792; 
S-10.The Battle of Friedland, June 14,1807; 
S-11.The Battle of Corunna, Jan.16,1809; 
S-12.The Battle of Aspern-Essling, May 21~22,1809; 
S-13.The Battle of Ocano, Sept.19,1809; 
S-14.The Battle of Salamanca, July 22,1812; 
S-15.The Battle of Leipzig, Oct.16~19,1813; 
S-16.The Battle of Craonne, Mar.7,1814; 
S-17.-A 400 Point Demonstration Game-1814.

Most of the 'Battles' covered here involve a single gaming table while the S-12.Aspern-Essling battle uses 2 tables and the S-15.Leipzig battle has 4-(!) tables being used for it's playing.

This is the second expansion module for the "Napoleon's Battles" miniatures Rules set. There are 5 additional Scenarios as well as Updated 'Errata' and clarifications for the previously released Game and 1st Module. There are 'New' concepts introduced which includes those such as 'Unknown' Tabletop Terrain Markers, the 'Campaign' Game and even some 'fast' Campaigns. With even some more Additional Optional Rules, an Expanded General Ratings Information chart, additional labels for the Scenarios included, a 'sheet' of Unknown Terrain Markers, another BLANK Information sheet, and detailed information on the MINOR Countries involved during this period of Military conflict.

The Scenarios included with this are: 
S-21.The Battle of Austerlitz-Dec.2,1805; 
S-22.The Battle of Vimiero-Aug.21,1808; 
S-23.The Battle of Wagram-July 6,1809; 
S-24.The Battle of Albuera-May 16, 1811; 
S-25.The Battle of Lutzen-May 2,1813.

The S-23.Wagram Scenario has 4-(!) tables being used for it's playing.

There are massive amounts of detail included with this concerning the Leaders & Commanders of just about every Nation or Minor country involved during the entire Campaigns of Napoleon! I'll add that they've incorrectly listed Scenarios 24~26 as they 'skipped' #23 but there are still 5 more of them and are listed correctly in the Table of Contents.

Quinto is a board and card game for ages 10 to adult.  The game is easy to understand and play because it contains familiar elements found in classic games, yet challenging enough for even the most demanding board and card game enthusiast.  Quinto, an advanced version of an ancient Roman board game, appeals to all ages.

Using playing cards, players compete to capture strategic positions on the game board and earn points.  The object of the game is to earn the most points.  Obtaining enough points to defeat your rival can be quite challenging because your opponent will try to capture and block your pieces.  The powerful "Wild Kings" and the high-scoring "Quick Quintos" can change the momentum of the game.

Each Quinto game includes:

one large, quad-fold playing card;
two decks of Quinto playing cards;
133 playing chips (red, blue, white);
score cards;
Game Manual; and
Warranty certificate

Every Quinto game comes with a 100% money back satisfaction guarantee.

BATTLE FOR THE BAYOU

A game of strategy and chance for 2 to 4 players ages 7 and up.

Join SWAMP THING&trade; and his heroic companions Tomahawk&trade; and Bayou Jack&trade; on a perilous journey to the heart of the bayou. Dr. Anton Arcane&trade; must be confronted, and his evil plot to destroy the bayou must be foiled.

Along the way, you will encounter The Un-men&trade;, Arcane's hideous henchmen, and at last, face Dr. Anton Arcane in the final climatic clash of this exciting Swamp Thing adventure!

Equipment:
&bull; Game Board;
&bull; 36 card SWAMP THING Deck;
&bull; 8 HERO Cards;
&bull; Battle Die;
&bull; 4 Pawns;
&bull; Complete instructions for play.

MANNERHEIMS CROSS: Finland at War 1939-1945 is a detailed new Advanced Tobruk system (ATS) game that brings the ATS gamer into the heart of the action on the Finnish Front, in the ultimate detail. Please note the game will be released in Finland as Suomi Sisu.

Mannerheims Cross: Finland at War 1939-1945 provides the orders of battle for Soviet, German and Russian forces during the famed Winter War (Talvisota), Continuation War (Jatkosota), and the final push to rid Finland of Nazi forces, the Lapland War (Lapinsota). Four game maps are included.

The complete Orders of Battle for the three wars are provided, with numerous German, Russian and Finnish troop types including Sissi, SS Nord reservists, Wehrmacht, and Russians ranging from crack Siberians to plodding Motti-bait. You'll also receive a collection of Finnish AFVs and guns, reflecting correct nomenclature for each weapon in Finnish service and including the BT-42 home-built assault-gun, the diminutive Komsomolets Tractor in Finnish service, and the ITPSV AA tank.

More importantly, you'll receive special rules and scenarios that aim to depict the unique nature of the conflict, fought in wet, dark wooded countryside, and involving Mottis and other Finnish tactics, like leap-frogging AT-guns and soldiers at the point of attack to work like cannon of an earlier era using so-called curving tactics.

IN EACH GAME YOU GET:

* A complete collection of color die-cut counters in 1/2&rdquo;, 5/8&rdquo; and 3/4&rdquo; sizes,
      representing the tanks, guns, and men that fought in the 1939-1940 and 1941-1945 campaigns in Finland;
    * SIX game maps on heavyweight stock;
    * The latest edition of the ATS rules of play;
    * Scenarios and Play Aids printed on separate heavyweight cards;
    * Two ten-sided dice.

